99 
100 //
101 // The type SINGLE_LIST_ENTRY is not suitable for use with SLISTs. For
102 // WIN64, an entry on an SLIST is required to be 16-byte aligned, while a
103 // SINGLE_LIST_ENTRY structure has only 8 byte alignment.
104 //
105 // Therefore, all SLIST code should use the SLIST_ENTRY type instead of the
106 // SINGLE_LIST_ENTRY type.
107 //
108 
109 #pragma warning(push)
110 #pragma warning(disable:4324) // structure padded due to align()
111 typedef struct DECLSPEC_ALIGN(16) _SLIST_ENTRY *PSLIST_ENTRY;
112 typedef struct DECLSPEC_ALIGN(16) _SLIST_ENTRY {
113  PSLIST_ENTRY Next;
114 } SLIST_ENTRY;
115 #pragma warning(pop)
116 
117 #else
118 
119 #define SLIST_ENTRY SINGLE_LIST_ENTRY
120 #define _SLIST_ENTRY _SINGLE_LIST_ENTRY
121 #define PSLIST_ENTRY PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY
122 
123 #endif
124 
125 #if defined(_WIN64)
126 
127 typedef struct DECLSPEC_ALIGN(16) _SLIST_HEADER {
128  ULONGLONG Alignment;
129  ULONGLONG Region;
130 } SLIST_HEADER;
131 
132 typedef struct _SLIST_HEADER *PSLIST_HEADER;
133 
134 #else
135 
136 typedef union _SLIST_HEADER {
137  ULONGLONG Alignment;
138  struct {
139  SLIST_ENTRY Next;
140  USHORT Depth;
141  USHORT Sequence;
142  };
143 } SLIST_HEADER, *PSLIST_HEADER;
144 
145 #endif

147 #endif

233 #define ASSERT( exp ) \
234  ((!(exp)) ? \
235  (RtlAssert( #exp, __FILE__, __LINE__, NULL ),FALSE) : \
236  TRUE)
237 
238 #define ASSERTMSG( msg, exp ) \
239  ((!(exp)) ? \
240  (RtlAssert( #exp, __FILE__, __LINE__, msg ),FALSE) : \
241  TRUE)
242 
243 #define RTL_SOFT_ASSERT(_exp) \
244  ((!(_exp)) ? \
245  (DbgPrint("%s(%d): Soft assertion failed\n Expression: %s\n", __FILE__, __LINE__, #_exp),FALSE) : \
246  TRUE)
247 
248 #define RTL_SOFT_ASSERTMSG(_msg, _exp) \
249  ((!(_exp)) ? \
250  (DbgPrint("%s(%d): Soft assertion failed\n Expression: %s\n Message: %s\n", __FILE__, __LINE__, #_exp, (_msg)),FALSE) : \
251  TRUE)
252

255 #define NT_ASSERT(_exp) \

260

333 VOID
334 FORCEINLINE
335 InitializeListHead(
336  IN PLIST_ENTRY ListHead

339  ListHead->Flink = ListHead->Blink = ListHead;

344 // IsListEmpty(
345 // PLIST_ENTRY ListHead
346 // );
347 //
348 
349 #define IsListEmpty(ListHead) \
350  ((ListHead)->Flink == (ListHead))

353 
354 BOOLEAN
355 FORCEINLINE
356 RemoveEntryList(
357  IN PLIST_ENTRY Entry
358  )
359 {
360  PLIST_ENTRY Blink;
361  PLIST_ENTRY Flink;
362 
363  Flink = Entry->Flink;
364  Blink = Entry->Blink;
365  Blink->Flink = Flink;
366  Flink->Blink = Blink;
367  return (BOOLEAN)(Flink == Blink);
368 }
369 
370 PLIST_ENTRY
371 FORCEINLINE
372 RemoveHeadList(
373  IN PLIST_ENTRY ListHead
374  )
375 {
376  PLIST_ENTRY Flink;
377  PLIST_ENTRY Entry;
378 
379  Entry = ListHead->Flink;
380  Flink = Entry->Flink;
381  ListHead->Flink = Flink;
382  Flink->Blink = ListHead;
383  return Entry;
384 }

388 PLIST_ENTRY

390 RemoveTailList(

395  PLIST_ENTRY Entry;
396 
397  Entry = ListHead->Blink;
398  Blink = Entry->Blink;
399  ListHead->Blink = Blink;
400  Blink->Flink = ListHead;

432  Entry->Flink = Flink;

439 //

441 // PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY
442 // PopEntryList(
443 // PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY ListHead
444 // );
445 //
446 
447 #define PopEntryList(ListHead) \
448  (ListHead)->Next;\
449  {\
450  PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY FirstEntry;\
451  FirstEntry = (ListHead)->Next;\
452  if (FirstEntry != NULL) { \
453  (ListHead)->Next = FirstEntry->Next;\
454  } \
455  }

462 // PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY Entry
463 // );
464 //
465 
466 #define PushEntryList(ListHead,Entry) \
467  (Entry)->Next = (ListHead)->Next; \
468  (ListHead)->Next = (Entry)

480 //
481 // This enumerated type is used as the function return value of the function
482 // that is used to search the tree for a key. FoundNode indicates that the
483 // function found the key. Insert as left indicates that the key was not found
484 // and the node should be inserted as the left child of the parent. Insert as
485 // right indicates that the key was not found and the node should be inserted
486 // as the right child of the parent.
487 //
488 typedef enum _TABLE_SEARCH_RESULT{
489  TableEmptyTree,
490  TableFoundNode,
491  TableInsertAsLeft,
492  TableInsertAsRight
493 } TABLE_SEARCH_RESULT;
494 
495 //
496 // The results of a compare can be less than, equal, or greater than.
497 //
498 
499 typedef enum _RTL_GENERIC_COMPARE_RESULTS {
500  GenericLessThan,
501  GenericGreaterThan,
502  GenericEqual
503 } RTL_GENERIC_COMPARE_RESULTS;
504 
505 //
506 // Define the Avl version of the generic table package. Note a generic table
507 // should really be an opaque type. We provide routines to manipulate the structure.
508 //
509 // A generic table is package for inserting, deleting, and looking up elements
510 // in a table (e.g., in a symbol table). To use this package the user
511 // defines the structure of the elements stored in the table, provides a
512 // comparison function, a memory allocation function, and a memory
513 // deallocation function.
514 //
515 // Note: the user compare function must impose a complete ordering among
516 // all of the elements, and the table does not allow for duplicate entries.
517 //
518 
519 //
520 // Add an empty typedef so that functions can reference the
521 // a pointer to the generic table struct before it is declared.
522 //
523 
524 struct _RTL_AVL_TABLE;
525 
526 //
527 // The comparison function takes as input pointers to elements containing
528 // user defined structures and returns the results of comparing the two
529 // elements.
530 //
531 
532 typedef
533 RTL_GENERIC_COMPARE_RESULTS
534 (NTAPI *PRTL_AVL_COMPARE_ROUTINE) (
535  struct _RTL_AVL_TABLE *Table,
536  PVOID FirstStruct,
537  PVOID SecondStruct
538  );
539 
540 //
541 // The allocation function is called by the generic table package whenever
542 // it needs to allocate memory for the table.
543 //
544 
545 typedef
546 PVOID
547 (NTAPI *PRTL_AVL_ALLOCATE_ROUTINE) (
548  struct _RTL_AVL_TABLE *Table,
549  CLONG ByteSize
550  );
551 
552 //
553 // The deallocation function is called by the generic table package whenever
554 // it needs to deallocate memory from the table that was allocated by calling
555 // the user supplied allocation function.
556 //
557 
558 typedef
559 VOID
560 (NTAPI *PRTL_AVL_FREE_ROUTINE) (
561  struct _RTL_AVL_TABLE *Table,
562  PVOID Buffer
563  );
564 
565 //
566 // The match function takes as input the user data to be matched and a pointer
567 // to some match data, which was passed along with the function pointer. It
568 // returns TRUE for a match and FALSE for no match.
569 //
570 // RTL_AVL_MATCH_FUNCTION returns
571 // STATUS_SUCCESS if the IndexRow matches
572 // STATUS_NO_MATCH if the IndexRow does not match, but the enumeration should
573 // continue
574 // STATUS_NO_MORE_MATCHES if the IndexRow does not match, and the enumeration
575 // should terminate
576 //
577 
578 
579 typedef
580 NTSTATUS
581 (NTAPI *PRTL_AVL_MATCH_FUNCTION) (
582  struct _RTL_AVL_TABLE *Table,
583  PVOID UserData,
584  PVOID MatchData
585  );
586 
587 //
588 // Define the balanced tree links and Balance field. (No Rank field
589 // defined at this time.)
590 //
591 // Callers should treat this structure as opaque!
592 //
593 // The root of a balanced binary tree is not a real node in the tree
594 // but rather points to a real node which is the root. It is always
595 // in the table below, and its fields are used as follows:
596 //
597 // Parent Pointer to self, to allow for detection of the root.
598 // LeftChild NULL
599 // RightChild Pointer to real root
600 // Balance Undefined, however it is set to a convenient value
601 // (depending on the algorithm) prior to rebalancing
602 // in insert and delete routines.
603 //
604 
605 typedef struct _RTL_BALANCED_LINKS {
606  struct _RTL_BALANCED_LINKS *Parent;
607  struct _RTL_BALANCED_LINKS *LeftChild;
608  struct _RTL_BALANCED_LINKS *RightChild;
609  CHAR Balance;
610  UCHAR Reserved[3];
611 } RTL_BALANCED_LINKS;
612 typedef RTL_BALANCED_LINKS *PRTL_BALANCED_LINKS;
613 
614 //
615 // To use the generic table package the user declares a variable of type
616 // GENERIC_TABLE and then uses the routines described below to initialize
617 // the table and to manipulate the table. Note that the generic table
618 // should really be an opaque type.
619 //
620 
621 typedef struct _RTL_AVL_TABLE {
622  RTL_BALANCED_LINKS BalancedRoot;
623  PVOID OrderedPointer;
624  ULONG WhichOrderedElement;
625  ULONG NumberGenericTableElements;
626  ULONG DepthOfTree;
627  PRTL_BALANCED_LINKS RestartKey;
628  ULONG DeleteCount;
629  PRTL_AVL_COMPARE_ROUTINE CompareRoutine;
630  PRTL_AVL_ALLOCATE_ROUTINE AllocateRoutine;
631  PRTL_AVL_FREE_ROUTINE FreeRoutine;
632  PVOID TableContext;
633 } RTL_AVL_TABLE;
634 typedef RTL_AVL_TABLE *PRTL_AVL_TABLE;
635 
636 //
637 // The procedure InitializeGenericTable takes as input an uninitialized
638 // generic table variable and pointers to the three user supplied routines.
639 // This must be called for every individual generic table variable before
640 // it can be used.
641 //
642 
643 NTSYSAPI
644 VOID
645 NTAPI
646 RtlInitializeGenericTableAvl (
647  PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table,
648  PRTL_AVL_COMPARE_ROUTINE CompareRoutine,
649  PRTL_AVL_ALLOCATE_ROUTINE AllocateRoutine,
650  PRTL_AVL_FREE_ROUTINE FreeRoutine,
651  PVOID TableContext
652  );
653 
654 //
655 // The function InsertElementGenericTable will insert a new element
656 // in a table. It does this by allocating space for the new element
657 // (this includes AVL links), inserting the element in the table, and
658 // then returning to the user a pointer to the new element. If an element
659 // with the same key already exists in the table the return value is a pointer
660 // to the old element. The optional output parameter NewElement is used
661 // to indicate if the element previously existed in the table. Note: the user
662 // supplied Buffer is only used for searching the table, upon insertion its
663 // contents are copied to the newly created element. This means that
664 // pointer to the input buffer will not point to the new element.
665 //
666 
667 NTSYSAPI
668 PVOID
669 NTAPI
670 RtlInsertElementGenericTableAvl (
671  PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table,
672  PVOID Buffer,
673  CLONG BufferSize,
674  PBOOLEAN NewElement OPTIONAL
675  );
676 
677 //
678 // The function InsertElementGenericTableFull will insert a new element
679 // in a table. It does this by allocating space for the new element
680 // (this includes AVL links), inserting the element in the table, and
681 // then returning to the user a pointer to the new element. If an element
682 // with the same key already exists in the table the return value is a pointer
683 // to the old element. The optional output parameter NewElement is used
684 // to indicate if the element previously existed in the table. Note: the user
685 // supplied Buffer is only used for searching the table, upon insertion its
686 // contents are copied to the newly created element. This means that
687 // pointer to the input buffer will not point to the new element.
688 // This routine is passed the NodeOrParent and SearchResult from a
689 // previous RtlLookupElementGenericTableFull.
690 //
691 
692 NTSYSAPI
693 PVOID
694 NTAPI
695 RtlInsertElementGenericTableFullAvl (
696  PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table,
697  PVOID Buffer,
698  CLONG BufferSize,
699  PBOOLEAN NewElement OPTIONAL,
700  PVOID NodeOrParent,
701  TABLE_SEARCH_RESULT SearchResult
702  );
703 
704 //
705 // The function DeleteElementGenericTable will find and delete an element
706 // from a generic table. If the element is located and deleted the return
707 // value is TRUE, otherwise if the element is not located the return value
708 // is FALSE. The user supplied input buffer is only used as a key in
709 // locating the element in the table.
710 //
711 
712 NTSYSAPI
713 BOOLEAN
714 NTAPI
715 RtlDeleteElementGenericTableAvl (
716  PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table,
717  PVOID Buffer
718  );
719 
720 //
721 // The function LookupElementGenericTable will find an element in a generic
722 // table. If the element is located the return value is a pointer to
723 // the user defined structure associated with the element, otherwise if
724 // the element is not located the return value is NULL. The user supplied
725 // input buffer is only used as a key in locating the element in the table.
726 //
727 
728 NTSYSAPI
729 PVOID
730 NTAPI
731 RtlLookupElementGenericTableAvl (
732  PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table,
733  PVOID Buffer
734  );
735 
736 //
737 // The function LookupElementGenericTableFull will find an element in a generic
738 // table. If the element is located the return value is a pointer to
739 // the user defined structure associated with the element. If the element is not
740 // located then a pointer to the parent for the insert location is returned. The
741 // user must look at the SearchResult value to determine which is being returned.
742 // The user can use the SearchResult and parent for a subsequent FullInsertElement
743 // call to optimize the insert.
744 //
745 
746 NTSYSAPI
747 PVOID
748 NTAPI
749 RtlLookupElementGenericTableFullAvl (
750  PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table,
751  PVOID Buffer,
752  OUT PVOID *NodeOrParent,
753  OUT TABLE_SEARCH_RESULT *SearchResult
754  );
755 
756 //
757 // The function EnumerateGenericTable will return to the caller one-by-one
758 // the elements of of a table. The return value is a pointer to the user
759 // defined structure associated with the element. The input parameter
760 // Restart indicates if the enumeration should start from the beginning
761 // or should return the next element. If the are no more new elements to
762 // return the return value is NULL. As an example of its use, to enumerate
763 // all of the elements in a table the user would write:
764 //
765 // for (ptr = EnumerateGenericTable(Table, TRUE);
766 // ptr != NULL;
767 // ptr = EnumerateGenericTable(Table, FALSE)) {
768 // :
769 // }
770 //
771 // NOTE: This routine does not modify the structure of the tree, but saves
772 // the last node returned in the generic table itself, and for this
773 // reason requires exclusive access to the table for the duration of
774 // the enumeration.
775 //
776 
777 NTSYSAPI
778 PVOID
779 NTAPI
780 RtlEnumerateGenericTableAvl (
781  PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table,
782  BOOLEAN Restart
783  );
784 
785 //
786 // The function EnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplaying will return to the
787 // caller one-by-one the elements of of a table. The return value is a
788 // pointer to the user defined structure associated with the element.
789 // The input parameter RestartKey indicates if the enumeration should
790 // start from the beginning or should return the next element. If the
791 // are no more new elements to return the return value is NULL. As an
792 // example of its use, to enumerate all of the elements in a table the
793 // user would write:
794 //
795 // RestartKey = NULL;
796 // for (ptr = EnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplaying(Table, &RestartKey);
797 // ptr != NULL;
798 // ptr = EnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplaying(Table, &RestartKey)) {
799 // :
800 // }
801 //
802 // If RestartKey is NULL, the package will start from the least entry in the
803 // table, otherwise it will start from the last entry returned.
804 //
805 // NOTE: This routine does not modify either the structure of the tree
806 // or the generic table itself, but must ensure that no deletes
807 // occur for the duration of the enumeration, typically by having
808 // at least shared access to the table for the duration.
809 //
810 
811 NTSYSAPI
812 PVOID
813 NTAPI
814 RtlEnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplayingAvl (
815  PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table,
816  PVOID *RestartKey
817  );
818 
819 //
820 // The function EnumerateGenericTableLikeADirectory will return to the
821 // caller one-by-one the elements of of a table. The return value is a
822 // pointer to the user defined structure associated with the element.
823 // The input parameter RestartKey indicates if the enumeration should
824 // start from the beginning or should return the next element. If the
825 // are no more new elements to return the return value is NULL. As an
826 // example of its use, to enumerate all of the elements in a table the
827 // user would write:
828 //
829 // RestartKey = NULL;
830 // for (ptr = EnumerateGenericTableLikeADirectory(Table, &RestartKey, ...);
831 // ptr != NULL;
832 // ptr = EnumerateGenericTableLikeADirectory(Table, &RestartKey, ...)) {
833 // :
834 // }
835 //
836 // If RestartKey is NULL, the package will start from the least entry in the
837 // table, otherwise it will start from the last entry returned.
838 //
839 // NOTE: This routine does not modify either the structure of the tree
840 // or the generic table itself. The table must only be acquired
841 // shared for the duration of this call, and all synchronization
842 // may optionally be dropped between calls. Enumeration is always
843 // correctly resumed in the most efficient manner possible via the
844 // IN OUT parameters provided.
845 //
846 // ****** Explain NextFlag. Directory enumeration resumes from a key
847 // requires more thought. Also need the match pattern and IgnoreCase.
848 // Should some structure be introduced to carry it all?
849 //
850 
851 NTSYSAPI
852 PVOID
853 NTAPI
854 RtlEnumerateGenericTableLikeADirectory (
855  IN PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table,
856  IN PRTL_AVL_MATCH_FUNCTION MatchFunction,
857  IN PVOID MatchData,
858  IN ULONG NextFlag,
859  IN OUT PVOID *RestartKey,
860  IN OUT PULONG DeleteCount,
861  IN OUT PVOID Buffer
862  );
863 
864 //
865 // The function GetElementGenericTable will return the i'th element
866 // inserted in the generic table. I = 0 implies the first element,
867 // I = (RtlNumberGenericTableElements(Table)-1) will return the last element
868 // inserted into the generic table. The type of I is ULONG. Values
869 // of I > than (NumberGenericTableElements(Table)-1) will return NULL. If
870 // an arbitrary element is deleted from the generic table it will cause
871 // all elements inserted after the deleted element to "move up".
872 
873 NTSYSAPI
874 PVOID
875 NTAPI
876 RtlGetElementGenericTableAvl (
877  PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table,
878  ULONG I
879  );
880 
881 //
882 // The function NumberGenericTableElements returns a ULONG value
883 // which is the number of generic table elements currently inserted
884 // in the generic table.
885 
886 NTSYSAPI
887 ULONG
888 NTAPI
889 RtlNumberGenericTableElementsAvl (
890  PRTL_AVL_TABLE Table
891  );

896 // FALSE otherwise.

898

906 //
907 // As an aid to allowing existing generic table users to do (in most
908 // cases) a single-line edit to switch over to Avl table use, we
909 // have the following defines and inline routine definitions which
910 // redirect calls and types. Note that the type override (performed
911 // by #define below) will not work in the unexpected event that someone
912 // has used a pointer or type specifier in their own #define, since
913 // #define processing is one pass and does not nest. The __inline
914 // declarations below do not have this limitation, however.
915 //
916 // To switch to using Avl tables, add the following line before your
917 // includes:
918 //
919 // #define RTL_USE_AVL_TABLES 0
920 //
921 
922 #ifdef RTL_USE_AVL_TABLES
923 
924 #undef PRTL_GENERIC_COMPARE_ROUTINE
925 #undef PRTL_GENERIC_ALLOCATE_ROUTINE
926 #undef PRTL_GENERIC_FREE_ROUTINE
927 #undef RTL_GENERIC_TABLE
928 #undef PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE
929 
930 #define PRTL_GENERIC_COMPARE_ROUTINE PRTL_AVL_COMPARE_ROUTINE
931 #define PRTL_GENERIC_ALLOCATE_ROUTINE PRTL_AVL_ALLOCATE_ROUTINE
932 #define PRTL_GENERIC_FREE_ROUTINE PRTL_AVL_FREE_ROUTINE
933 #define RTL_GENERIC_TABLE RTL_AVL_TABLE
934 #define PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE PRTL_AVL_TABLE
935 
936 #define RtlInitializeGenericTable RtlInitializeGenericTableAvl
937 #define RtlInsertElementGenericTable RtlInsertElementGenericTableAvl
938 #define RtlInsertElementGenericTableFull RtlInsertElementGenericTableFullAvl
939 #define RtlDeleteElementGenericTable RtlDeleteElementGenericTableAvl
940 #define RtlLookupElementGenericTable RtlLookupElementGenericTableAvl
941 #define RtlLookupElementGenericTableFull RtlLookupElementGenericTableFullAvl
942 #define RtlEnumerateGenericTable RtlEnumerateGenericTableAvl
943 #define RtlEnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplaying RtlEnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplayingAvl
944 #define RtlGetElementGenericTable RtlGetElementGenericTableAvl
945 #define RtlNumberGenericTableElements RtlNumberGenericTableElementsAvl
946 #define RtlIsGenericTableEmpty RtlIsGenericTableEmptyAvl
947 
948 #endif // RTL_USE_AVL_TABLES

951 //
952 // Define the splay links and the associated manipulation macros and
953 // routines. Note that the splay_links should be an opaque type.
954 // Routine are provided to traverse and manipulate the structure.
955 //
956 
957 typedef struct _RTL_SPLAY_LINKS {
958  struct _RTL_SPLAY_LINKS *Parent;
959  struct _RTL_SPLAY_LINKS *LeftChild;
960  struct _RTL_SPLAY_LINKS *RightChild;
961 } RTL_SPLAY_LINKS;
962 typedef RTL_SPLAY_LINKS *PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS;
963 
964 //
965 // The macro procedure InitializeSplayLinks takes as input a pointer to
966 // splay link and initializes its substructure. All splay link nodes must
967 // be initialized before they are used in the different splay routines and
968 // macros.
969 //
970 // VOID
971 // RtlInitializeSplayLinks (
972 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS Links
973 // );
974 //
975 
976 #define RtlInitializeSplayLinks(Links) { \
977  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS _SplayLinks; \
978  _SplayLinks = (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(Links); \
979  _SplayLinks->Parent = _SplayLinks; \
980  _SplayLinks->LeftChild = NULL; \
981  _SplayLinks->RightChild = NULL; \
982  }
983 
984 //
985 // The macro function Parent takes as input a pointer to a splay link in a
986 // tree and returns a pointer to the splay link of the parent of the input
987 // node. If the input node is the root of the tree the return value is
988 // equal to the input value.
989 //
990 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS
991 // RtlParent (
992 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS Links
993 // );
994 //
995 
996 #define RtlParent(Links) ( \
997  (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(Links)->Parent \
998  )
999 
1000 //
1001 // The macro function LeftChild takes as input a pointer to a splay link in
1002 // a tree and returns a pointer to the splay link of the left child of the
1003 // input node. If the left child does not exist, the return value is NULL.
1004 //
1005 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS
1006 // RtlLeftChild (
1007 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS Links
1008 // );
1009 //
1010 
1011 #define RtlLeftChild(Links) ( \
1012  (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(Links)->LeftChild \
1013  )
1014 
1015 //
1016 // The macro function RightChild takes as input a pointer to a splay link
1017 // in a tree and returns a pointer to the splay link of the right child of
1018 // the input node. If the right child does not exist, the return value is
1019 // NULL.
1020 //
1021 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS
1022 // RtlRightChild (
1023 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS Links
1024 // );
1025 //
1026 
1027 #define RtlRightChild(Links) ( \
1028  (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(Links)->RightChild \
1029  )
1030 
1031 //
1032 // The macro function IsRoot takes as input a pointer to a splay link
1033 // in a tree and returns TRUE if the input node is the root of the tree,
1034 // otherwise it returns FALSE.
1035 //
1036 // BOOLEAN
1037 // RtlIsRoot (
1038 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS Links
1039 // );
1040 //
1041 
1042 #define RtlIsRoot(Links) ( \
1043  (RtlParent(Links) == (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(Links)) \
1044  )
1045 
1046 //
1047 // The macro function IsLeftChild takes as input a pointer to a splay link
1048 // in a tree and returns TRUE if the input node is the left child of its
1049 // parent, otherwise it returns FALSE.
1050 //
1051 // BOOLEAN
1052 // RtlIsLeftChild (
1053 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS Links
1054 // );
1055 //
1056 
1057 #define RtlIsLeftChild(Links) ( \
1058  (RtlLeftChild(RtlParent(Links)) == (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(Links)) \
1059  )
1060 
1061 //
1062 // The macro function IsRightChild takes as input a pointer to a splay link
1063 // in a tree and returns TRUE if the input node is the right child of its
1064 // parent, otherwise it returns FALSE.
1065 //
1066 // BOOLEAN
1067 // RtlIsRightChild (
1068 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS Links
1069 // );
1070 //
1071 
1072 #define RtlIsRightChild(Links) ( \
1073  (RtlRightChild(RtlParent(Links)) == (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(Links)) \
1074  )
1075 
1076 //
1077 // The macro procedure InsertAsLeftChild takes as input a pointer to a splay
1078 // link in a tree and a pointer to a node not in a tree. It inserts the
1079 // second node as the left child of the first node. The first node must not
1080 // already have a left child, and the second node must not already have a
1081 // parent.
1082 //
1083 // VOID
1084 // RtlInsertAsLeftChild (
1085 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS ParentLinks,
1086 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS ChildLinks
1087 // );
1088 //
1089 
1090 #define RtlInsertAsLeftChild(ParentLinks,ChildLinks) { \
1091  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS _SplayParent; \
1092  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS _SplayChild; \
1093  _SplayParent = (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(ParentLinks); \
1094  _SplayChild = (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(ChildLinks); \
1095  _SplayParent->LeftChild = _SplayChild; \
1096  _SplayChild->Parent = _SplayParent; \
1097  }
1098 
1099 //
1100 // The macro procedure InsertAsRightChild takes as input a pointer to a splay
1101 // link in a tree and a pointer to a node not in a tree. It inserts the
1102 // second node as the right child of the first node. The first node must not
1103 // already have a right child, and the second node must not already have a
1104 // parent.
1105 //
1106 // VOID
1107 // RtlInsertAsRightChild (
1108 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS ParentLinks,
1109 // PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS ChildLinks
1110 // );
1111 //
1112 
1113 #define RtlInsertAsRightChild(ParentLinks,ChildLinks) { \
1114  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS _SplayParent; \
1115  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS _SplayChild; \
1116  _SplayParent = (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(ParentLinks); \
1117  _SplayChild = (PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS)(ChildLinks); \
1118  _SplayParent->RightChild = _SplayChild; \
1119  _SplayChild->Parent = _SplayParent; \
1120  }
1121

1125 // root of the splayed tree.

1221 
1222 //
1223 // Define the generic table package. Note a generic table should really
1224 // be an opaque type. We provide routines to manipulate the structure.
1225 //
1226 // A generic table is package for inserting, deleting, and looking up elements
1227 // in a table (e.g., in a symbol table). To use this package the user
1228 // defines the structure of the elements stored in the table, provides a
1229 // comparison function, a memory allocation function, and a memory
1230 // deallocation function.
1231 //
1232 // Note: the user compare function must impose a complete ordering among
1233 // all of the elements, and the table does not allow for duplicate entries.
1234 //
1235 
1236 //
1237 // Do not do the following defines if using Avl
1238 //
1239 
1240 #ifndef RTL_USE_AVL_TABLES
1241 
1242 //
1243 // Add an empty typedef so that functions can reference the
1244 // a pointer to the generic table struct before it is declared.
1245 //
1246 
1247 struct _RTL_GENERIC_TABLE;
1248 
1249 //
1250 // The comparison function takes as input pointers to elements containing
1251 // user defined structures and returns the results of comparing the two
1252 // elements.
1253 //
1254 
1255 typedef
1256 RTL_GENERIC_COMPARE_RESULTS
1257 (NTAPI *PRTL_GENERIC_COMPARE_ROUTINE) (
1258  struct _RTL_GENERIC_TABLE *Table,
1259  PVOID FirstStruct,
1260  PVOID SecondStruct
1261  );
1262 
1263 //
1264 // The allocation function is called by the generic table package whenever
1265 // it needs to allocate memory for the table.
1266 //
1267 
1268 typedef
1269 PVOID
1270 (NTAPI *PRTL_GENERIC_ALLOCATE_ROUTINE) (
1271  struct _RTL_GENERIC_TABLE *Table,
1272  CLONG ByteSize
1273  );
1274 
1275 //
1276 // The deallocation function is called by the generic table package whenever
1277 // it needs to deallocate memory from the table that was allocated by calling
1278 // the user supplied allocation function.
1279 //
1280 
1281 typedef
1282 VOID
1283 (NTAPI *PRTL_GENERIC_FREE_ROUTINE) (
1284  struct _RTL_GENERIC_TABLE *Table,
1285  PVOID Buffer
1286  );
1287 
1288 //
1289 // To use the generic table package the user declares a variable of type
1290 // GENERIC_TABLE and then uses the routines described below to initialize
1291 // the table and to manipulate the table. Note that the generic table
1292 // should really be an opaque type.
1293 //
1294 
1295 typedef struct _RTL_GENERIC_TABLE {
1296  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS TableRoot;
1297  LIST_ENTRY InsertOrderList;
1298  PLIST_ENTRY OrderedPointer;
1299  ULONG WhichOrderedElement;
1300  ULONG NumberGenericTableElements;
1301  PRTL_GENERIC_COMPARE_ROUTINE CompareRoutine;
1302  PRTL_GENERIC_ALLOCATE_ROUTINE AllocateRoutine;
1303  PRTL_GENERIC_FREE_ROUTINE FreeRoutine;
1304  PVOID TableContext;
1305 } RTL_GENERIC_TABLE;
1306 typedef RTL_GENERIC_TABLE *PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE;
1307 
1308 //
1309 // The procedure InitializeGenericTable takes as input an uninitialized
1310 // generic table variable and pointers to the three user supplied routines.
1311 // This must be called for every individual generic table variable before
1312 // it can be used.
1313 //
1314 
1315 NTSYSAPI
1316 VOID
1317 NTAPI
1318 RtlInitializeGenericTable (
1319  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table,
1320  PRTL_GENERIC_COMPARE_ROUTINE CompareRoutine,
1321  PRTL_GENERIC_ALLOCATE_ROUTINE AllocateRoutine,
1322  PRTL_GENERIC_FREE_ROUTINE FreeRoutine,
1323  PVOID TableContext
1324  );
1325 
1326 //
1327 // The function InsertElementGenericTable will insert a new element
1328 // in a table. It does this by allocating space for the new element
1329 // (this includes splay links), inserting the element in the table, and
1330 // then returning to the user a pointer to the new element. If an element
1331 // with the same key already exists in the table the return value is a pointer
1332 // to the old element. The optional output parameter NewElement is used
1333 // to indicate if the element previously existed in the table. Note: the user
1334 // supplied Buffer is only used for searching the table, upon insertion its
1335 // contents are copied to the newly created element. This means that
1336 // pointer to the input buffer will not point to the new element.
1337 //
1338 
1339 NTSYSAPI
1340 PVOID
1341 NTAPI
1342 RtlInsertElementGenericTable (
1343  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table,
1344  PVOID Buffer,
1345  CLONG BufferSize,
1346  PBOOLEAN NewElement OPTIONAL
1347  );
1348 
1349 //
1350 // The function InsertElementGenericTableFull will insert a new element
1351 // in a table. It does this by allocating space for the new element
1352 // (this includes splay links), inserting the element in the table, and
1353 // then returning to the user a pointer to the new element. If an element
1354 // with the same key already exists in the table the return value is a pointer
1355 // to the old element. The optional output parameter NewElement is used
1356 // to indicate if the element previously existed in the table. Note: the user
1357 // supplied Buffer is only used for searching the table, upon insertion its
1358 // contents are copied to the newly created element. This means that
1359 // pointer to the input buffer will not point to the new element.
1360 // This routine is passed the NodeOrParent and SearchResult from a
1361 // previous RtlLookupElementGenericTableFull.
1362 //
1363 
1364 NTSYSAPI
1365 PVOID
1366 NTAPI
1367 RtlInsertElementGenericTableFull (
1368  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table,
1369  PVOID Buffer,
1370  CLONG BufferSize,
1371  PBOOLEAN NewElement OPTIONAL,
1372  PVOID NodeOrParent,
1373  TABLE_SEARCH_RESULT SearchResult
1374  );
1375 
1376 //
1377 // The function DeleteElementGenericTable will find and delete an element
1378 // from a generic table. If the element is located and deleted the return
1379 // value is TRUE, otherwise if the element is not located the return value
1380 // is FALSE. The user supplied input buffer is only used as a key in
1381 // locating the element in the table.
1382 //
1383 
1384 NTSYSAPI
1385 BOOLEAN
1386 NTAPI
1387 RtlDeleteElementGenericTable (
1388  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table,
1389  PVOID Buffer
1390  );
1391 
1392 //
1393 // The function LookupElementGenericTable will find an element in a generic
1394 // table. If the element is located the return value is a pointer to
1395 // the user defined structure associated with the element, otherwise if
1396 // the element is not located the return value is NULL. The user supplied
1397 // input buffer is only used as a key in locating the element in the table.
1398 //
1399 
1400 NTSYSAPI
1401 PVOID
1402 NTAPI
1403 RtlLookupElementGenericTable (
1404  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table,
1405  PVOID Buffer
1406  );
1407 
1408 //
1409 // The function LookupElementGenericTableFull will find an element in a generic
1410 // table. If the element is located the return value is a pointer to
1411 // the user defined structure associated with the element. If the element is not
1412 // located then a pointer to the parent for the insert location is returned. The
1413 // user must look at the SearchResult value to determine which is being returned.
1414 // The user can use the SearchResult and parent for a subsequent FullInsertElement
1415 // call to optimize the insert.
1416 //
1417 
1418 NTSYSAPI
1419 PVOID
1420 NTAPI
1421 RtlLookupElementGenericTableFull (
1422  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table,
1423  PVOID Buffer,
1424  OUT PVOID *NodeOrParent,
1425  OUT TABLE_SEARCH_RESULT *SearchResult
1426  );
1427 
1428 //
1429 // The function EnumerateGenericTable will return to the caller one-by-one
1430 // the elements of of a table. The return value is a pointer to the user
1431 // defined structure associated with the element. The input parameter
1432 // Restart indicates if the enumeration should start from the beginning
1433 // or should return the next element. If the are no more new elements to
1434 // return the return value is NULL. As an example of its use, to enumerate
1435 // all of the elements in a table the user would write:
1436 //
1437 // for (ptr = EnumerateGenericTable(Table, TRUE);
1438 // ptr != NULL;
1439 // ptr = EnumerateGenericTable(Table, FALSE)) {
1440 // :
1441 // }
1442 //
1443 //
1444 // PLEASE NOTE:
1445 //
1446 // If you enumerate a GenericTable using RtlEnumerateGenericTable, you
1447 // will flatten the table, turning it into a sorted linked list.
1448 // To enumerate the table without perturbing the splay links, use
1449 // RtlEnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplaying
1450 
1451 NTSYSAPI
1452 PVOID
1453 NTAPI
1454 RtlEnumerateGenericTable (
1455  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table,
1456  BOOLEAN Restart
1457  );
1458 
1459 //
1460 // The function EnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplaying will return to the
1461 // caller one-by-one the elements of of a table. The return value is a
1462 // pointer to the user defined structure associated with the element.
1463 // The input parameter RestartKey indicates if the enumeration should
1464 // start from the beginning or should return the next element. If the
1465 // are no more new elements to return the return value is NULL. As an
1466 // example of its use, to enumerate all of the elements in a table the
1467 // user would write:
1468 //
1469 // RestartKey = NULL;
1470 // for (ptr = EnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplaying(Table, &RestartKey);
1471 // ptr != NULL;
1472 // ptr = EnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplaying(Table, &RestartKey)) {
1473 // :
1474 // }
1475 //
1476 // If RestartKey is NULL, the package will start from the least entry in the
1477 // table, otherwise it will start from the last entry returned.
1478 //
1479 //
1480 // Note that unlike RtlEnumerateGenericTable, this routine will NOT perturb
1481 // the splay order of the tree.
1482 //
1483 
1484 NTSYSAPI
1485 PVOID
1486 NTAPI
1487 RtlEnumerateGenericTableWithoutSplaying (
1488  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table,
1489  PVOID *RestartKey
1490  );
1491 
1492 //
1493 // The function GetElementGenericTable will return the i'th element
1494 // inserted in the generic table. I = 0 implies the first element,
1495 // I = (RtlNumberGenericTableElements(Table)-1) will return the last element
1496 // inserted into the generic table. The type of I is ULONG. Values
1497 // of I > than (NumberGenericTableElements(Table)-1) will return NULL. If
1498 // an arbitrary element is deleted from the generic table it will cause
1499 // all elements inserted after the deleted element to "move up".
1500 
1501 NTSYSAPI
1502 PVOID
1503 NTAPI
1504 RtlGetElementGenericTable(
1505  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table,
1506  ULONG I
1507  );
1508 
1509 //
1510 // The function NumberGenericTableElements returns a ULONG value
1511 // which is the number of generic table elements currently inserted
1512 // in the generic table.
1513 
1514 NTSYSAPI
1515 ULONG
1516 NTAPI
1517 RtlNumberGenericTableElements(
1518  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table
1519  );
1520 
1521 //
1522 // The function IsGenericTableEmpty will return to the caller TRUE if
1523 // the input table is empty (i.e., does not contain any elements) and
1524 // FALSE otherwise.
1525 //
1526 
1527 NTSYSAPI
1528 BOOLEAN
1529 NTAPI
1530 RtlIsGenericTableEmpty (
1531  PRTL_GENERIC_TABLE Table
1532  );
1533 
1534 #endif // RTL_USE_AVL_TABLES

2115 
2116 
2117 //
2118 // The following flags specify how the Name field of a RTL_QUERY_REGISTRY_TABLE
2119 // entry is interpreted. A NULL name indicates the end of the table.
2120 //
2121 
2122 #define RTL_QUERY_REGISTRY_SUBKEY 0x00000001 // Name is a subkey and remainder of
2123  // table or until next subkey are value
2124  // names for that subkey to look at.
2125 
2126 #define RTL_QUERY_REGISTRY_TOPKEY 0x00000002 // Reset current key to original key for
2127  // this and all following table entries.
2128 
2129 #define RTL_QUERY_REGISTRY_REQUIRED 0x00000004 // Fail if no match found for this table
2130  // entry.
2131 
2132 #define RTL_QUERY_REGISTRY_NOVALUE 0x00000008 // Used to mark a table entry that has no
2133  // value name, just wants a call out, not
2134  // an enumeration of all values.
2135 
2136 #define RTL_QUERY_REGISTRY_NOEXPAND 0x00000010 // Used to suppress the expansion of
2137  // REG_MULTI_SZ into multiple callouts or
2138  // to prevent the expansion of environment
2139  // variable values in REG_EXPAND_SZ
2140 
2141 #define RTL_QUERY_REGISTRY_DIRECT 0x00000020 // QueryRoutine field ignored. EntryContext
2142  // field points to location to store value.
2143  // For null terminated strings, EntryContext
2144  // points to UNICODE_STRING structure that
2145  // that describes maximum size of buffer.
2146  // If .Buffer field is NULL then a buffer is
2147  // allocated.
2148  //
2149 
2150 #define RTL_QUERY_REGISTRY_DELETE 0x00000040 // Used to delete value keys after they
2151  // are queried.
2152

2154 NTSTATUS

2159  IN PRTL_QUERY_REGISTRY_TABLE QueryTable,
2160  IN PVOID Context,
2161  IN PVOID Environment OPTIONAL
2162  );

2211 #define RTL_REGISTRY_CONTROL 2 // \Registry\Machine\System\CurrentControlSet\Control
2212 #define RTL_REGISTRY_WINDOWS_NT 3 // \Registry\Machine\Software\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion
2213 #define RTL_REGISTRY_DEVICEMAP 4 // \Registry\Machine\Hardware\DeviceMap
2214 #define RTL_REGISTRY_USER 5 // \Registry\User\CurrentUser
2215 #define RTL_REGISTRY_MAXIMUM 6
2216 #define RTL_REGISTRY_HANDLE 0x40000000 // Low order bits are registry handle

3307 typedef struct _GENERATE_NAME_CONTEXT {
3308

3310  // The structure is divided into two strings. The Name, and extension.
3311  // Each part contains the value that was last inserted in the name.

3321

3323  WCHAR ExtensionBuffer[4]; // e.g., ".exe"
3324

3326 
3327 } GENERATE_NAME_CONTEXT;

3619 //
3620 //
3621 // Compression package types and procedures.
3622 //
3623 
3624 #define COMPRESSION_FORMAT_NONE (0x0000) // winnt
3625 #define COMPRESSION_FORMAT_DEFAULT (0x0001) // winnt
3626 #define COMPRESSION_FORMAT_LZNT1 (0x0002) // winnt
3627 
3628 #define COMPRESSION_ENGINE_STANDARD (0x0000) // winnt
3629 #define COMPRESSION_ENGINE_MAXIMUM (0x0100) // winnt
3630 #define COMPRESSION_ENGINE_HIBER (0x0200) // winnt
3631 
3632 //
3633 // Compressed Data Information structure. This structure is
3634 // used to describe the state of a compressed data buffer,
3635 // whose uncompressed size is known. All compressed chunks
3636 // described by this structure must be compressed with the
3637 // same format. On compressed reads, this entire structure
3638 // is an output, and on compressed writes the entire structure
3639 // is an input.
3640 //
3641 
3642 typedef struct _COMPRESSED_DATA_INFO {
3643 
3644  //
3645  // Code for the compression format (and engine) as
3646  // defined in ntrtl.h. Note that COMPRESSION_FORMAT_NONE
3647  // and COMPRESSION_FORMAT_DEFAULT are invalid if
3648  // any of the described chunks are compressed.
3649  //
3650 
3651  USHORT CompressionFormatAndEngine;
3652 
3653  //
3654  // Since chunks and compression units are expected to be
3655  // powers of 2 in size, we express then log2. So, for
3656  // example (1 << ChunkShift) == ChunkSizeInBytes. The
3657  // ClusterShift indicates how much space must be saved
3658  // to successfully compress a compression unit - each
3659  // successfully compressed compression unit must occupy
3660  // at least one cluster less in bytes than an uncompressed
3661  // compression unit.
3662  //
3663 
3664  UCHAR CompressionUnitShift;
3665  UCHAR ChunkShift;
3666  UCHAR ClusterShift;
3667  UCHAR Reserved;
3668 
3669  //
3670  // This is the number of entries in the CompressedChunkSizes
3671  // array.
3672  //
3673 
3674  USHORT NumberOfChunks;
3675 
3676  //
3677  // This is an array of the sizes of all chunks resident
3678  // in the compressed data buffer. There must be one entry
3679  // in this array for each chunk possible in the uncompressed
3680  // buffer size. A size of FSRTL_CHUNK_SIZE indicates the
3681  // corresponding chunk is uncompressed and occupies exactly
3682  // that size. A size of 0 indicates that the corresponding
3683  // chunk contains nothing but binary 0's, and occupies no
3684  // space in the compressed data. All other sizes must be
3685  // less than FSRTL_CHUNK_SIZE, and indicate the exact size
3686  // of the compressed data in bytes.
3687  //
3688 
3689  ULONG CompressedChunkSizes[ANYSIZE_ARRAY];
3690 
3691 } COMPRESSED_DATA_INFO;
3692 typedef COMPRESSED_DATA_INFO *PCOMPRESSED_DATA_INFO;
3693 
3694 NTSYSAPI
3695 NTSTATUS
3696 NTAPI
3697 RtlGetCompressionWorkSpaceSize (
3698  IN USHORT CompressionFormatAndEngine,
3699  OUT PULONG CompressBufferWorkSpaceSize,
3700  OUT PULONG CompressFragmentWorkSpaceSize
3701  );

4110 NTAPI
4111 RtlImageNtHeader(
4112  PVOID Base
4113  );
4114 
4115 #define RTL_MEG (1024UL * 1024UL)
4116 #define RTLP_IMAGE_MAX_DOS_HEADER ( 256UL * RTL_MEG)
4117 
4118 #if !defined(MIDL_PASS)
4119 __inline
4120 PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS
4121 NTAPI
4122 RtlpImageNtHeader (
4123  IN PVOID Base
4124  )
4125 
4126 /*++
4127 
4128 Routine Description:
4129 
4130  This function returns the address of the NT Header.
4131 
4132 Arguments:
4133 
4134  Base - Supplies the base of the image.
4135 
4136 Return Value:
4137 
4138  Returns the address of the NT Header.
4139 
4140 --*/
4141 
4142 {
4143  PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS NtHeaders = NULL;
4144  if (Base != NULL && Base != (PVOID)-1) {
4145  __try {
4146  if ((((PIMAGE_DOS_HEADER)Base)->e_magic == IMAGE_DOS_SIGNATURE) &&
4147  (((ULONG)((PIMAGE_DOS_HEADER)Base)->e_lfanew) < RTLP_IMAGE_MAX_DOS_HEADER)) {
4148  NtHeaders = (PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS)((PCHAR)Base + ((PIMAGE_DOS_HEADER)Base)->e_lfanew);
4149  if (NtHeaders->Signature != IMAGE_NT_SIGNATURE) {
4150  NtHeaders = NULL;
4151  }
4152  }
4153  }
4154  __except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
4155  NtHeaders = NULL;
4156  }
4157  }
4158  return NtHeaders;
4159 }
4160 #endif

4224 //
4225 // Fast primitives to compare, move, and zero memory
4226 //

4228 // begin_winnt begin_ntndis
4229 
4230 #if _DBG_MEMCPY_INLINE_ && !defined(MIDL_PASS) && !defined(_MEMCPY_INLINE_) && !defined(_CRTBLD)
4231 #define _MEMCPY_INLINE_
4232 FORCEINLINE
4233 PVOID
4234 __cdecl
4235 memcpy_inline (
4236  void *dst,
4237  const void *src,
4238  size_t size
4239  )
4240 {
4241  //
4242  // Make sure the source and destination do not overlap such that the
4243  // move destroys the destination.
4244  //
4245  if (((char *)dst > (char *)src) &&
4246  ((char *)dst < ((char *)src + size))) {
4247  __debugbreak();
4248  }
4249  return memcpy(dst, src, size);
4250 }
4251 #define memcpy memcpy_inline
4252 #endif
4253 
4254 NTSYSAPI
4255 SIZE_T
4256 NTAPI
4257 RtlCompareMemory (
4258  const VOID *Source1,
4259  const VOID *Source2,
4260  SIZE_T Length
4261  );
4262 
4263 
4264 #define RtlEqualMemory(Destination,Source,Length) (!memcmp((Destination),(Source),(Length)))
4265 #define RtlMoveMemory(Destination,Source,Length) memmove((Destination),(Source),(Length))
4266 #define RtlCopyMemory(Destination,Source,Length) memcpy((Destination),(Source),(Length))
4267 #define RtlFillMemory(Destination,Length,Fill) memset((Destination),(Fill),(Length))
4268 #define RtlZeroMemory(Destination,Length) memset((Destination),0,(Length))
4269 
4270 
4271 #if !defined(MIDL_PASS)
4272 
4273 FORCEINLINE
4274 PVOID
4275 RtlSecureZeroMemory(
4276  IN PVOID ptr,
4277  IN SIZE_T cnt
4278  )
4279 {
4280  volatile char *vptr = (volatile char *)ptr;
4281 
4282 #if defined(_M_AMD64)
4283 
4284  __stosb((PUCHAR)((ULONG64)vptr), 0, cnt);
4285 
4286 #else
4287 
4288  while (cnt) {
4289  *vptr = 0;
4290  vptr++;
4291  cnt--;
4292  }
4293 
4294 #endif
4295 
4296  return ptr;
4297 }
4298 
4299 #endif

4334 NTSYSAPI
4335 SIZE_T
4336 NTAPI
4337 RtlCompareMemoryUlong (
4338  PVOID Source,
4339  SIZE_T Length,
4340  ULONG Pattern
4341  );
4342 
4343 #if defined(_M_AMD64)
4344 
4345 #if !defined(MIDL_PASS)
4346 
4347 FORCEINLINE
4348 VOID
4349 RtlFillMemoryUlong (
4350  PVOID Destination,
4351  SIZE_T Length,
4352  ULONG Pattern
4353  )
4354 
4355 {
4356 
4357  PULONG Address = (PULONG)Destination;
4358 
4359  //
4360  // If the number of DWORDs is not zero, then fill the specified buffer
4361  // with the specified pattern.
4362  //
4363 
4364  if ((Length /= 4) != 0) {
4365 
4366  //
4367  // If the destination is not quadword aligned (ignoring low bits),
4368  // then align the destination by storing one DWORD.
4369  //
4370 
4371  if (((ULONG64)Address & 4) != 0) {
4372  *Address = Pattern;
4373  if ((Length -= 1) == 0) {
4374  return;
4375  }
4376 
4377  Address += 1;
4378  }
4379 
4380  //
4381  // If the number of QWORDs is not zero, then fill the destination
4382  // buffer a QWORD at a time.
4383  //
4384 
4385  __stosq((PULONG64)(Address),
4386  Pattern | ((ULONG64)Pattern << 32),
4387  Length / 2);
4388 
4389  if ((Length & 1) != 0) {
4390  Address[Length - 1] = Pattern;
4391  }
4392  }
4393 
4394  return;
4395 }
4396 
4397 #define RtlFillMemoryUlonglong(Destination, Length, Pattern) \
4398  __stosq((PULONG64)(Destination), Pattern, (Length) / 8)
4399 
4400 #endif
4401 
4402 #else
4403 
4404 NTSYSAPI
4405 VOID
4406 NTAPI
4407 RtlFillMemoryUlong (
4408  PVOID Destination,
4409  SIZE_T Length,
4410  ULONG Pattern
4411  );
4412 
4413 NTSYSAPI
4414 VOID
4415 NTAPI
4416 RtlFillMemoryUlonglong (
4417  PVOID Destination,
4418  SIZE_T Length,
4419  ULONGLONG Pattern
4420  );
4421 
4422 #endif

4779 __inline
4780 ULONG
4781 NTAPI

4784  IN ULONG Divisor,
4785  IN PULONG Remainder OPTIONAL
4786  )
4787 {

4793  }
4794 
4795  return Quotient;

4835 //

4837 //
4838 
4839 #if defined(_AMD64_)
4840 
4841 DECLSPEC_DEPRECATED_DDK // Use native __int64 math
4842 __inline
4843 LARGE_INTEGER
4844 NTAPI
4845 RtlExtendedMagicDivide (
4846  LARGE_INTEGER Dividend,
4847  LARGE_INTEGER MagicDivisor,
4848  CCHAR ShiftCount
4849  )
4850 
4851 {
4852 
4853  LARGE_INTEGER Quotient;
4854 
4855  if (Dividend.QuadPart >= 0) {
4856  Quotient.QuadPart = UnsignedMultiplyHigh(Dividend.QuadPart,
4857  (ULONG64)MagicDivisor.QuadPart);
4858 
4859  } else {
4860  Quotient.QuadPart = UnsignedMultiplyHigh(-Dividend.QuadPart,
4861  (ULONG64)MagicDivisor.QuadPart);
4862  }
4863 
4864  Quotient.QuadPart = (ULONG64)Quotient.QuadPart >> ShiftCount;
4865  if (Dividend.QuadPart < 0) {
4866  Quotient.QuadPart = - Quotient.QuadPart;
4867  }
4868 
4869  return Quotient;
4870 }

5102 //
5103 // Large integer comparison routines.
5104 //
5105 
5106 #if PRAGMA_DEPRECATED_DDK
5107 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerGreaterThan) // Use native __int64 math
5108 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerGreaterThanOrEqualTo) // Use native __int64 math
5109 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerEqualTo) // Use native __int64 math
5110 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerNotEqualTo) // Use native __int64 math
5111 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerLessThan) // Use native __int64 math
5112 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerLessThanOrEqualTo) // Use native __int64 math
5113 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerGreaterThanZero) // Use native __int64 math
5114 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerGreaterOrEqualToZero) // Use native __int64 math
5115 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerEqualToZero) // Use native __int64 math
5116 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerNotEqualToZero) // Use native __int64 math
5117 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerLessThanZero) // Use native __int64 math
5118 #pragma deprecated(RtlLargeIntegerLessOrEqualToZero) // Use native __int64 math
5119 #endif
5120 
5121 #define RtlLargeIntegerGreaterThan(X,Y) ( \
5122  (((X).HighPart == (Y).HighPart) && ((X).LowPart > (Y).LowPart)) || \
5123  ((X).HighPart > (Y).HighPart) \
5124 )
5125 
5126 #define RtlLargeIntegerGreaterThanOrEqualTo(X,Y) ( \
5127  (((X).HighPart == (Y).HighPart) && ((X).LowPart >= (Y).LowPart)) || \
5128  ((X).HighPart > (Y).HighPart) \
5129 )
5130 
5131 #define RtlLargeIntegerEqualTo(X,Y) ( \
5132  !(((X).LowPart ^ (Y).LowPart) | ((X).HighPart ^ (Y).HighPart)) \
5133 )
5134 
5135 #define RtlLargeIntegerNotEqualTo(X,Y) ( \
5136  (((X).LowPart ^ (Y).LowPart) | ((X).HighPart ^ (Y).HighPart)) \
5137 )
5138 
5139 #define RtlLargeIntegerLessThan(X,Y) ( \
5140  (((X).HighPart == (Y).HighPart) && ((X).LowPart < (Y).LowPart)) || \
5141  ((X).HighPart < (Y).HighPart) \
5142 )
5143 
5144 #define RtlLargeIntegerLessThanOrEqualTo(X,Y) ( \
5145  (((X).HighPart == (Y).HighPart) && ((X).LowPart <= (Y).LowPart)) || \
5146  ((X).HighPart < (Y).HighPart) \
5147 )
5148 
5149 #define RtlLargeIntegerGreaterThanZero(X) ( \
5150  (((X).HighPart == 0) && ((X).LowPart > 0)) || \
5151  ((X).HighPart > 0 ) \
5152 )
5153 
5154 #define RtlLargeIntegerGreaterOrEqualToZero(X) ( \
5155  (X).HighPart >= 0 \
5156 )
5157 
5158 #define RtlLargeIntegerEqualToZero(X) ( \
5159  !((X).LowPart | (X).HighPart) \
5160 )
5161 
5162 #define RtlLargeIntegerNotEqualToZero(X) ( \
5163  ((X).LowPart | (X).HighPart) \
5164 )
5165 
5166 #define RtlLargeIntegerLessThanZero(X) ( \
5167  ((X).HighPart < 0) \
5168 )
5169 
5170 #define RtlLargeIntegerLessOrEqualToZero(X) ( \
5171  ((X).HighPart < 0) || !((X).LowPart | (X).HighPart) \
5172 )
5173 
5174 #endif // !defined(MIDL_PASS)

5342 // begin_ntddk begin_wdm begin_nthal begin_ntifs
5343 //
5344 // The following macros store and retrieve USHORTS and ULONGS from potentially
5345 // unaligned addresses, avoiding alignment faults. they should probably be
5346 // rewritten in assembler
5347 //
5348 
5349 #define SHORT_SIZE (sizeof(USHORT))
5350 #define SHORT_MASK (SHORT_SIZE - 1)
5351 #define LONG_SIZE (sizeof(LONG))
5352 #define LONGLONG_SIZE (sizeof(LONGLONG))
5353 #define LONG_MASK (LONG_SIZE - 1)
5354 #define LONGLONG_MASK (LONGLONG_SIZE - 1)
5355 #define LOWBYTE_MASK 0x00FF
5356 
5357 #define FIRSTBYTE(VALUE) ((VALUE) & LOWBYTE_MASK)
5358 #define SECONDBYTE(VALUE) (((VALUE) >> 8) & LOWBYTE_MASK)
5359 #define THIRDBYTE(VALUE) (((VALUE) >> 16) & LOWBYTE_MASK)
5360 #define FOURTHBYTE(VALUE) (((VALUE) >> 24) & LOWBYTE_MASK)
5361 
5362 //
5363 // if MIPS Big Endian, order of bytes is reversed.
5364 //
5365 
5366 #define SHORT_LEAST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT 0
5367 #define SHORT_MOST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT 1
5368 
5369 #define LONG_LEAST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT 0
5370 #define LONG_3RD_MOST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT 1
5371 #define LONG_2ND_MOST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT 2
5372 #define LONG_MOST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT 3
5373 
5374 //++
5375 //
5376 // VOID
5377 // RtlStoreUshort (
5378 // PUSHORT ADDRESS
5379 // USHORT VALUE
5380 // )
5381 //
5382 // Routine Description:
5383 //
5384 // This macro stores a USHORT value in at a particular address, avoiding
5385 // alignment faults.
5386 //
5387 // Arguments:
5388 //
5389 // ADDRESS - where to store USHORT value
5390 // VALUE - USHORT to store
5391 //
5392 // Return Value:
5393 //
5394 // none.
5395 //
5396 //--
5397 
5398 #if defined(_AMD64_)
5399 
5400 #define RtlStoreUshort(ADDRESS,VALUE) \
5401  *(USHORT UNALIGNED *)(ADDRESS) = (VALUE)
5402 
5403 #else
5404 
5405 #define RtlStoreUshort(ADDRESS,VALUE) \
5406  if ((ULONG_PTR)(ADDRESS) & SHORT_MASK) { \
5407  ((PUCHAR) (ADDRESS))[SHORT_LEAST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT] = (UCHAR)(FIRSTBYTE(VALUE)); \
5408  ((PUCHAR) (ADDRESS))[SHORT_MOST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT ] = (UCHAR)(SECONDBYTE(VALUE)); \
5409  } \
5410  else { \
5411  *((PUSHORT) (ADDRESS)) = (USHORT) VALUE; \
5412  }
5413 
5414 #endif
5415 
5416 //++
5417 //
5418 // VOID
5419 // RtlStoreUlong (
5420 // PULONG ADDRESS
5421 // ULONG VALUE
5422 // )
5423 //
5424 // Routine Description:
5425 //
5426 // This macro stores a ULONG value in at a particular address, avoiding
5427 // alignment faults.
5428 //
5429 // Arguments:
5430 //
5431 // ADDRESS - where to store ULONG value
5432 // VALUE - ULONG to store
5433 //
5434 // Return Value:
5435 //
5436 // none.
5437 //
5438 // Note:
5439 // Depending on the machine, we might want to call storeushort in the
5440 // unaligned case.
5441 //
5442 //--
5443 
5444 
5445 #if defined(_AMD64_)
5446 
5447 #define RtlStoreUlong(ADDRESS,VALUE) \
5448  *(ULONG UNALIGNED *)(ADDRESS) = (VALUE)
5449 
5450 #else
5451 
5452 #define RtlStoreUlong(ADDRESS,VALUE) \
5453  if ((ULONG_PTR)(ADDRESS) & LONG_MASK) { \
5454  ((PUCHAR) (ADDRESS))[LONG_LEAST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT ] = (UCHAR)(FIRSTBYTE(VALUE)); \
5455  ((PUCHAR) (ADDRESS))[LONG_3RD_MOST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT ] = (UCHAR)(SECONDBYTE(VALUE)); \
5456  ((PUCHAR) (ADDRESS))[LONG_2ND_MOST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT ] = (UCHAR)(THIRDBYTE(VALUE)); \
5457  ((PUCHAR) (ADDRESS))[LONG_MOST_SIGNIFICANT_BIT ] = (UCHAR)(FOURTHBYTE(VALUE)); \
5458  } \
5459  else { \
5460  *((PULONG) (ADDRESS)) = (ULONG) (VALUE); \
5461  }
5462 
5463 #endif
5464 
5465 //++
5466 //
5467 // VOID
5468 // RtlStoreUlonglong (
5469 // PULONGLONG ADDRESS
5470 // ULONG VALUE
5471 // )
5472 //
5473 // Routine Description:
5474 //
5475 // This macro stores a ULONGLONG value in at a particular address, avoiding
5476 // alignment faults.
5477 //
5478 // Arguments:
5479 //
5480 // ADDRESS - where to store ULONGLONG value
5481 // VALUE - ULONGLONG to store
5482 //
5483 // Return Value:
5484 //
5485 // none.
5486 //
5487 //--
5488 
5489 #if defined(_AMD64_)
5490 
5491 #define RtlStoreUlonglong(ADDRESS,VALUE) \
5492  *(ULONGLONG UNALIGNED *)(ADDRESS) = (VALUE)
5493 
5494 #else
5495 
5496 #define RtlStoreUlonglong(ADDRESS,VALUE) \
5497  if ((ULONG_PTR)(ADDRESS) & LONGLONG_MASK) { \
5498  RtlStoreUlong((ULONG_PTR)(ADDRESS), \
5499  (ULONGLONG)(VALUE) & 0xFFFFFFFF); \
5500  RtlStoreUlong((ULONG_PTR)(ADDRESS)+sizeof(ULONG), \
5501  (ULONGLONG)(VALUE) >> 32); \
5502  } else { \
5503  *((PULONGLONG)(ADDRESS)) = (ULONGLONG)(VALUE); \
5504  }
5505 
5506 #endif
5507 
5508 //++
5509 //
5510 // VOID
5511 // RtlStoreUlongPtr (
5512 // PULONG_PTR ADDRESS
5513 // ULONG_PTR VALUE
5514 // )
5515 //
5516 // Routine Description:
5517 //
5518 // This macro stores a ULONG_PTR value in at a particular address, avoiding
5519 // alignment faults.
5520 //
5521 // Arguments:
5522 //
5523 // ADDRESS - where to store ULONG_PTR value
5524 // VALUE - ULONG_PTR to store
5525 //
5526 // Return Value:
5527 //
5528 // none.
5529 //
5530 //--
5531 
5532 #ifdef _WIN64
5533 
5534 #define RtlStoreUlongPtr(ADDRESS,VALUE) \
5535  RtlStoreUlonglong(ADDRESS,VALUE)
5536 
5537 #else
5538 
5539 #define RtlStoreUlongPtr(ADDRESS,VALUE) \
5540  RtlStoreUlong(ADDRESS,VALUE)
5541 
5542 #endif
5543 
5544 //++
5545 //
5546 // VOID
5547 // RtlRetrieveUshort (
5548 // PUSHORT DESTINATION_ADDRESS
5549 // PUSHORT SOURCE_ADDRESS
5550 // )
5551 //
5552 // Routine Description:
5553 //
5554 // This macro retrieves a USHORT value from the SOURCE address, avoiding
5555 // alignment faults. The DESTINATION address is assumed to be aligned.
5556 //
5557 // Arguments:
5558 //
5559 // DESTINATION_ADDRESS - where to store USHORT value
5560 // SOURCE_ADDRESS - where to retrieve USHORT value from
5561 //
5562 // Return Value:
5563 //
5564 // none.
5565 //
5566 //--
5567 
5568 #if defined(_AMD64_)
5569 
5570 #define RtlRetrieveUshort(DEST_ADDRESS,SRC_ADDRESS) \
5571  *(USHORT UNALIGNED *)(DEST_ADDRESS) = *(PUSHORT)(SRC_ADDRESS)
5572 
5573 #else
5574 
5575 #define RtlRetrieveUshort(DEST_ADDRESS,SRC_ADDRESS) \
5576  if ((ULONG_PTR)SRC_ADDRESS & SHORT_MASK) { \
5577  ((PUCHAR) DEST_ADDRESS)[0] = ((PUCHAR) SRC_ADDRESS)[0]; \
5578  ((PUCHAR) DEST_ADDRESS)[1] = ((PUCHAR) SRC_ADDRESS)[1]; \
5579  } \
5580  else { \
5581  *((PUSHORT) DEST_ADDRESS) = *((PUSHORT) SRC_ADDRESS); \
5582  } \
5583 
5584 #endif
5585 
5586 //++
5587 //
5588 // VOID
5589 // RtlRetrieveUlong (
5590 // PULONG DESTINATION_ADDRESS
5591 // PULONG SOURCE_ADDRESS
5592 // )
5593 //
5594 // Routine Description:
5595 //
5596 // This macro retrieves a ULONG value from the SOURCE address, avoiding
5597 // alignment faults. The DESTINATION address is assumed to be aligned.
5598 //
5599 // Arguments:
5600 //
5601 // DESTINATION_ADDRESS - where to store ULONG value
5602 // SOURCE_ADDRESS - where to retrieve ULONG value from
5603 //
5604 // Return Value:
5605 //
5606 // none.
5607 //
5608 // Note:
5609 // Depending on the machine, we might want to call retrieveushort in the
5610 // unaligned case.
5611 //
5612 //--
5613 
5614 #if defined(_AMD64_)
5615 
5616 #define RtlRetrieveUlong(DEST_ADDRESS,SRC_ADDRESS) \
5617  *(ULONG UNALIGNED *)(DEST_ADDRESS) = *(PULONG)(SRC_ADDRESS)
5618 
5619 #else
5620 
5621 #define RtlRetrieveUlong(DEST_ADDRESS,SRC_ADDRESS) \
5622  if ((ULONG_PTR)SRC_ADDRESS & LONG_MASK) { \
5623  ((PUCHAR) DEST_ADDRESS)[0] = ((PUCHAR) SRC_ADDRESS)[0]; \
5624  ((PUCHAR) DEST_ADDRESS)[1] = ((PUCHAR) SRC_ADDRESS)[1]; \
5625  ((PUCHAR) DEST_ADDRESS)[2] = ((PUCHAR) SRC_ADDRESS)[2]; \
5626  ((PUCHAR) DEST_ADDRESS)[3] = ((PUCHAR) SRC_ADDRESS)[3]; \
5627  } \
5628  else { \
5629  *((PULONG) DEST_ADDRESS) = *((PULONG) SRC_ADDRESS); \
5630  }
5631 
5632 #endif
5633 
5634 // end_ntddk end_wdm

5636 //++
5637 //
5638 // PCHAR
5639 // RtlOffsetToPointer (
5640 // PVOID Base,
5641 // ULONG Offset
5642 // )
5643 //
5644 // Routine Description:
5645 //
5646 // This macro generates a pointer which points to the byte that is 'Offset'
5647 // bytes beyond 'Base'. This is useful for referencing fields within
5648 // self-relative data structures.
5649 //
5650 // Arguments:
5651 //
5652 // Base - The address of the base of the structure.
5653 //
5654 // Offset - An unsigned integer offset of the byte whose address is to
5655 // be generated.
5656 //

5658 //
5659 // A PCHAR pointer to the byte that is 'Offset' bytes beyond 'Base'.
5660 //
5661 //
5662 //--

5670 // RtlPointerToOffset (

5673 // )
5674 //
5675 // Routine Description:
5676 //
5677 // This macro calculates the offset from Base to Pointer. This is useful
5678 // for producing self-relative offsets for structures.
5679 //
5680 // Arguments:
5681 //
5682 // Base - The address of the base of the structure.
5683 //
5684 // Pointer - A pointer to a field, presumably within the structure
5685 // pointed to by Base. This value must be larger than that specified

5687 //

5689 //
5690 // A ULONG offset from Base to Pointer.

5692 //

5914 // bitmap at the specified location. If the bit is set a value of 1 is
5915 // returned otherwise a value of 0 is returned.
5916 //
5917 // ULONG
5918 // RtlCheckBit (
5919 // PRTL_BITMAP BitMapHeader,
5920 // ULONG BitPosition
5921 // );
5922 //
5923 //
5924 // To implement CheckBit the macro retrieves the longword containing the
5925 // bit in question, shifts the longword to get the bit in question into the
5926 // low order bit position and masks out all other bits.
5927 //
5928 
5929 #if defined(_M_AMD64) && !defined(MIDL_PASS)
5930 
5931 FORCEINLINE
5932 BOOLEAN
5933 RtlCheckBit (
5934  PRTL_BITMAP BitMapHeader,
5935  ULONG BitPosition
5936  )
5937 
5938 {
5939 
5940  return BitTest((LONG const *)BitMapHeader->Buffer, BitPosition);
5941 }
5942 
5943 #else
5944 
5945 #define RtlCheckBit(BMH,BP) ((((BMH)->Buffer[(BP) / 32]) >> ((BP) % 32)) & 0x1)
5946 
5947 #endif

6191  ((L1)->HighPart == (L2)->HighPart))
6192

6196 // PLUID L1
6197 // );

6207  LONG Long
6208  )

6210  LUID TempLuid;

6212

6214  TempLuid.LowPart = TempLi.LowPart;
6215  TempLuid.HighPart = TempLi.HighPart;
6216  return(TempLuid);
6217 }

6230  return(TempLuid);

6807 
6808 //
6809 // Macro to make a known ACE type ready for applying to a specific object type.
6810 // This is done by mapping any generic access types, and clearing
6811 // the special access types field.
6812 //
6813 // This routine should only be used on DSA define ACEs.
6814 //
6815 // Parameters:
6816 //
6817 // Ace - Points to an ACE to be applied. Only ACEs that are not
6818 // InheritOnly are mapped.
6819 //
6820 // Mapping - Points to a generic mapping array for the type of
6821 // object the ACE is being applied to.
6822 //
6823 
6824  //
6825  // Clear invalid bits. Note that ACCESS_SYSTEM_SECURITY is
6826  // valid in SACLs, but not in DACLs. So, leave it in audit and
6827  // alarm ACEs, but clear it in access allowed and denied ACEs.
6828  //
6829 
6830 #define RtlApplyAceToObject(Ace,Mapping) \
6831  if (!FlagOn((Ace)->AceFlags, INHERIT_ONLY_ACE) ) { \
6832  RtlApplyGenericMask( Ace, &((PKNOWN_ACE)(Ace))->Mask, Mapping ); \
6833  }
6834 
6835 // Same as above, but don't modify the mask in the ACE itself.
6836 #define RtlApplyGenericMask(Ace, Mask, Mapping) { \
6837  RtlMapGenericMask( (Mask), (Mapping)); \
6838  \
6839  if ( (((PKNOWN_ACE)(Ace))->Header.AceType == ACCESS_ALLOWED_ACE_TYPE) || \
6840  (((PKNOWN_ACE)(Ace))->Header.AceType == ACCESS_DENIED_ACE_TYPE) || \
6841  (((PKNOWN_ACE)(Ace))->Header.AceType == ACCESS_ALLOWED_COMPOUND_ACE_TYPE) || \
6842  (((PKNOWN_ACE)(Ace))->Header.AceType == ACCESS_ALLOWED_OBJECT_ACE_TYPE) || \
6843  (((PKNOWN_ACE)(Ace))->Header.AceType == ACCESS_DENIED_OBJECT_ACE_TYPE) ) { \
6844  *(Mask) &= (Mapping)->GenericAll; \
6845  } else { \
6846  *(Mask) &= ((Mapping)->GenericAll | \
6847  ACCESS_SYSTEM_SECURITY); \
6848  } \
6849  }
6850 
6851 //
6852 // Service to get the primary domain name/sid of the local machine
6853 // Callable only from user mode.
6854 //
6855 
6856 //NTSYSAPI
6857 NTSTATUS
6858 NTAPI
6859 RtlGetPrimaryDomain(
6860  IN ULONG SidLength,
6861  OUT PBOOLEAN PrimaryDomainPresent,
6862  OUT PUNICODE_STRING PrimaryDomainName,
6863  OUT PUSHORT RequiredNameLength,
6864  OUT PSID PrimaryDomainSid OPTIONAL,
6865  OUT PULONG RequiredSidLength
6866  );

6869 // Temporary user mode Registry system services //

7224 typedef struct _RTL_RANGE {
7225 
7226  //
7227  // The start of the range
7228  //
7229  ULONGLONG Start; // Read only
7230 
7231  //
7232  // The end of the range
7233  //
7234  ULONGLONG End; // Read only
7235 
7236  //
7237  // Data the user passed in when they created the range
7238  //
7239  PVOID UserData; // Read/Write
7240 
7241  //
7242  // The owner of the range
7243  //
7244  PVOID Owner; // Read/Write
7245 
7246  //
7247  // User defined flags the user specified when they created the range
7248  //
7249  UCHAR Attributes; // Read/Write
7250 
7251  //
7252  // Flags (RTL_RANGE_*)
7253  //
7254  UCHAR Flags; // Read only
7255 
7256 } RTL_RANGE, *PRTL_RANGE;

7262 typedef struct _RTL_RANGE_LIST {
7263 
7264  //
7265  // The list of ranges
7266  //
7267  LIST_ENTRY ListHead;
7268 
7269  //
7270  // These always come in useful
7271  //
7272  ULONG Flags; // use RANGE_LIST_FLAG_*
7273 
7274  //
7275  // The number of entries in the list
7276  //
7277  ULONG Count;
7278 
7279  //
7280  // Every time an add/delete operation is performed on the list this is
7281  // incremented. It is checked during iteration to ensure that the list
7282  // hasn't changed between GetFirst/GetNext or GetNext/GetNext calls
7283  //
7284  ULONG Stamp;
7285 
7286 } RTL_RANGE_LIST, *PRTL_RANGE_LIST;

7412  RtlGetNextRange((Iterator), &(Current), FALSE) \
7413  )

7466 //

7468 // big-endian and vice-versa.

7470 
7471 #if (defined(_M_IX86) && (_MSC_FULL_VER > 13009037)) || ((defined(_M_AMD64)) && (_MSC_FULL_VER > 13009175))

7473 extern "C" {
7474 #endif
7475 unsigned short __cdecl _byteswap_ushort(unsigned short);
7476 unsigned long __cdecl _byteswap_ulong (unsigned long);
7477 unsigned __int64 __cdecl _byteswap_uint64(unsigned __int64);
7478 #ifdef __cplusplus
7479 }
7480 #endif
7481 #pragma intrinsic(_byteswap_ushort)
7482 #pragma intrinsic(_byteswap_ulong)
7483 #pragma intrinsic(_byteswap_uint64)
7484 
7485 #define RtlUshortByteSwap(_x) _byteswap_ushort((USHORT)(_x))
7486 #define RtlUlongByteSwap(_x) _byteswap_ulong((_x))
7487 #define RtlUlonglongByteSwap(_x) _byteswap_uint64((_x))
7488 #else

7491 RtlUshortByteSwap(

7855 
7856 FORCEINLINE
7857 BOOLEAN
7858 RtlUnsignedAddWithCarryOut32(
7859  unsigned __int32 *pc,
7860  unsigned __int32 a,
7861  unsigned __int32 b
7862  )
7863 {
7864  unsigned __int32 c;
7865 
7866  c = a + b;
7867  *pc = c;
7868  return (c >= a && c >= b) ? 0 : 1;
7869 }
7870 
7871 FORCEINLINE
7872 BOOLEAN
7873 RtlUnsignedAddWithCarryOut64(
7874  unsigned __int64 *pc,
7875  unsigned __int64 a,
7876  unsigned __int64 b
7877  )
7878 {
7879  unsigned __int64 c;
7880 
7881  c = a + b;
7882  *pc = c;
7883  return (c >= a && c >= b) ? 0 : 1;
7884 }
7885 
7886 FORCEINLINE
7887 BOOLEAN
7888 RtlSignedAddWithOverflowOut32(
7889  __int32 *pc,
7890  __int32 a,
7891  __int32 b
7892  )
7893 {
7894  __int32 c;
7895 
7896  c = a + b;
7897  *pc = c;
7898 
7899  //
7900  // negative + positive -> no overflow
7901  // positive + negative -> no overflow
7902  // positive + positive -> overflow if result is not positive
7903  // negative + negative -> overflow if result is not negative
7904  //
7905  // aka -- no overflow if result's sign is the same as either input's sign.
7906  //
7907  return (((c < 0) == (a < 0)) || ((c < 0) == (b < 0))) ? 0 : 1;
7908 }
7909 
7910 FORCEINLINE
7911 BOOLEAN
7912 RtlSignedAddWithOverflowOut64(
7913  __int64 *pc,
7914  __int64 a,
7915  __int64 b
7916  )
7917 {
7918  __int64 c;
7919 
7920  c = a + b;
7921  *pc = c;
7922 
7923  return (((c < 0) == (a < 0)) || ((c < 0) == (b < 0))) ? 0 : 1;
7924 }
7925 
7926 #define RTLP_ADD_WITH_CARRY_OUT(FunctionName, Type, BaseFunction, BaseType) \
7927 FORCEINLINE \
7928 BOOLEAN \
7929 FunctionName( \
7930  Type *pc, \
7931  Type a, \
7932  Type b \
7933  ) \
7934 { \
7935  return BaseFunction((BaseType*)pc, a, b); \
7936 }

7942 
7943 #define RTLP_ADD_WITH_CARRY_OUT_UNSIGNED64(FunctionName, Type) \
